article.description:
Dirk Nowitzki had 33 points and 10 rebounds and the Mavericks
beat the Trail Blazers for the second time in three nights, leading
by as many as 26 in a 109-92 victory Thursday night.
article.headline: Dirk pours in 33 as Mavericks put away Blazers
article.linkText: Dirk pours in 33 as Mavericks put away Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- This time, the Dallas Mavericks had an easier time putting away Portland. Dirk Nowitzki had 33 points and 10 rebounds and the Mavericks beat the Trail Blazers for the second time in three nights, leading by as many as 26 in a 109-92 victory Thursday night. Zach Randolph had 29 points for the Blazers after scoring 33 points and grabbing eight rebounds in a 93-87 loss to Dallas on Tuesday. Mavericks coach Avery Johnson complained that his team was lethargic after Tuesday's game, and said he needed to do something to get its attention. He was more pleased with the result Thursday. "We put together a decent effort from start to finish," he said. Jason Terry had 19 points and Devin Harris added 12 points and seven assists for the Mavericks. Reserve Sebastian Telfair had 12 points and eight assists for Portland, which has lost nine of 10 games since the All-Star break and sits in last place in the Western Conference. Coach Nate McMillan planned on asking his players hard questions at practice Friday, saying it was important to determine "who wants to be here." Portland's Darius Miles scored nine points in 17 minutes Thursday, but was benched after picking up his fifth foul in the third quarter. Miles lost his starting spot last week and has been listless and inconsistent since returning Feb. 13 from a knee injury. "If that's how he feels, that's how he feels," Miles said about McMillan. "I have no problem with that. No problem at all." The Mavericks built up a 16-point lead in the first half before settling for a 54-40 advantage at the break. Stackhouse found Nowitzki for a 16-footer that increased the lead to 73-47 in the second half. Nowitzki made 15 of 16 free throws for Dallas, which finished 31-of-35 from the line. The Mavs, who allowed Portland to score 13 points before their first field goal Tuesday, shot 55 percent and had a 30-25 advantage on the boards Thursday. Dallas plays nine of its next 12 games on the road, and fatigue has been cited as a reason for recent struggles -- including a loss to Phoenix and poor performances against Portland and Charlotte. But Terry, who was coming off a 26-point game Tuesday, believes the Mavericks have enough charge in them to keep winning and satisfy their coach, who is 64-13 since taking over from Don Nelson last year. "It's just a matter of getting it done," Terry said. "(Johnson's) done all the motivating he can do. He's not going to need to do no more because the veterans are going to step up and get this going in the right direction." Josh Howard sat out for the second straight game with an ankle sprain. Harris took Howard's spot in the lineup and Dallas got good production from the bench, including 13 points from Marquis Daniels, 11 from Jerry Stackhouse and nine points and five rebounds from Erick Dampier. "Right now, I think we're kind of moving backwards," Telfair said. "Quitting -- as in not giving the same effort. We're still coming to work every night, but we're not giving that effort."

Game notes
The Mavericks are 20-8 on the road. ... Dallas has beaten the Blazers in all four meetings this year and has won 10 straight in the series.
